# Flutter Architecture Rules

## Folder structure

```
lib/
├── core/           # App-wide infrastructure (theme, router, config, network, utils)
├── features/       # One directory per vertical slice
│   └── <feature>/
│       ├── data/         # Repositories impl, API clients, local DAO adapters
│       ├── domain/       # Entities, abstract repositories, use-cases
│       └── presentation/ # Screens, widgets, Riverpod providers
└── shared/         # Reusable widgets and models used by 2+ features
```

## Layer rules

- `presentation/` imports `domain/` only — never another feature's `data/`.
- `data/` implements `domain/` interfaces — never imports `presentation/`.
- Cross-feature sharing goes through `core/` or `shared/`, never feature→feature.
- `core/` has no dependency on any feature.

## Naming conventions

| Type | Naming | File |
|------|--------|------|
| Screen | `FooScreen` | `foo_screen.dart` |
| Widget | `FooCard`, `FooButton` | `foo_card.dart` |
| Provider | `fooProvider` | `foo_provider.dart` or `foo_providers.dart` |
| Repository (abstract) | `FooRepository` | `foo_repository.dart` |
| Repository (impl) | `FooRepositoryImpl` | `foo_repository_impl.dart` |
| Entity | `Foo` (Freezed) | `foo.dart` |
| Use-case | `GetFooUseCase` | `get_foo_use_case.dart` |

## Adding a new feature checklist

1. Create `lib/features/<name>/{data,domain,presentation}/` directories.
2. Define entity in `domain/entities/`.
3. Define repository interface in `domain/repositories/`.
4. Implement repository in `data/repositories/`.
5. Create Riverpod provider in `presentation/providers/`.
6. Build screen in `presentation/<name>_screen.dart`.
7. Federate routes in `presentation/<name>_routes.dart`; spread them into
   `core/router/app_router.dart` (don't add feature routes to `AppRoutes` directly).

## Multi-vehicle transport features

Bus, flight, and private car (and future train/ship/cruise/hotel) are each a
**fully independent feature slice** — not variants of one "booking" feature.
Each owns its entire flow: search form, results/quote, passenger or contact
capture, payment, and ticket/voucher. This is deliberate: each mode has a
genuinely different backend contract and session shape (see
`docs/superpowers/specs/2026-07-08-multi-vehicle-architecture-design.md`).

- Never add a `mode`/`vehicleType` switch inside one feature's screens or
  notifier — that's how bus ended up with leaked flight fields
  (`flightClass`, flight-only round-trip) before this convention existed.
  If two modes need the same *flow shape*, copy the feature skeleton; don't
  branch inside a shared one.
- Cross-feature imports between transport features (e.g. `flight/` importing
  from `bus/`) are not allowed, same as any other feature pair — only
  `core/` and `shared/` are shared.
- Stateless presentational atoms with no booking logic (price row, payment
  tile, labeled input) may live in `shared/widgets` once two features need
  the identical thing — lift on second use, not preemptively.
- `home` only knows, per mode: its search-form widget, its search-params
  type, and its entry route. It must never contain per-mode booking logic.

## What NOT to do

- Don't put business logic inside a widget's `build()`.
- Don't hardcode strings or colors — use `AppColors`, `AppTypography`, localization keys.
- Don't navigate with `Navigator.push` — use `context.go()` from go_router.
- Don't call APIs directly from presentation — always go through a repository.
